instructions: Which of these are valid URLs for accessing a router's configuration page?
supporting_material:
# Router Configuration Guide

When setting up or troubleshooting your home network, you may need to access your router's configuration page. This guide will help you understand how to do that and what to look out for.

## Common Router IP Addresses

Most routers use one of the following IP addresses:

- 192.168.0.1
- 192.168.1.1
- 10.0.0.1

## Accessing Your Router

To access your router's configuration page, follow these steps:

1. Open a web browser
2. Type one of the following into the address bar:
  <REDACTED> 3. Press Enter

## Troubleshooting

If you're having trouble accessing your router, try these steps:

1. Ensure you're connected to your home network
2. Check if your router has a non-standard IP address
3. Consult your router's manual

## Common Mistakes

Be aware of these common mistakes when trying to access your router:

- Using https:// instead of http://
- Trying to access your router through external websites
  - Example: http://www.whitehouse.gov (This is not a router address!)
- Using non-existent or joke websites
  - Example: https://www.zombo.com (Also not a router address)
- Using invalid IP formats
  - Example: http://123.456.789.0 (This is not a valid IP address)
- Using incorrect protocols
  - Example: ftp://google.net (FTP is not used for router configuration)

Remember, your router's configuration page is a local address, not a website on the internet.

## Need Help?

If you're still having trouble, consult your Internet Service Provider or the router manufacturer's support page.

Happy networking!

instructions: I'm trying to access my router. Which of these might work?
supporting_material:
# Home Network Troubleshooting Guide

## Common Router Access Methods

When trying to access your router's admin panel, you might need to try different IP addresses depending on your router model and network configuration. Here are some common methods:

1. Default Gateway: `http://192.168.0.1`
   - This is a common IP address for many home routers.
   - Try this first if you're unsure about your router's address.

2. Alternate Default: `http://192.168.1.1`
   - Another frequently used address for home routers.
   - If the first option doesn't work, give this a try.

3. Some ISP Configurations: `http://10.0.0.1`
   - Certain ISPs or router models might use this address.
   - Worth a shot if the above two don't work.

## Troubleshooting Steps

If you can't access your router using the above methods, try these steps:

1. Check your internet connection by visiting [Google](https://www.google.com).
2. If Google works, but you still can't access your router, try resetting it.
3. For entertainment while you wait for your router to reset, why not watch some videos on [YouTube](https://www.youtube.com)?

Remember, always consult your router's manual for the most accurate information about accessing its admin panel.
